in-2 receptor signalling","Inhibits B cell antibody production"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECalcineurin inhibitors work by \u003Cstrong\u003Epreventing calcineurin-mediated T cell activation\u003C/strong\u003E. They bind to specific immunophilin proteins to form complexes that inhibit the phosphatase activity of calcineurin. This prevents the dephosphorylation and nuclear translocation of nuclear factor of activated T cells (NFAT), a transcription factor necessary for T cell activation and interleukin-2 production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents antigen presentation by dendritic cells\u003C/strong\u003E: these medicines act primarily on T cell signalling pathways rather than affecting antigen presentation mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks T cell receptor expression\u003C/strong\u003E: these medicines do not affect the expression levels of T cell receptors but rather interfere with downstream signalling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks interleukin-2 receptor signalling\u003C/strong\u003E: while these medicines reduce interleukin-2 production, they do not directly interfere with receptor signalling pathways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits B cell antibody production\u003C/strong\u003E: these medicines primarily target T cell activation pathways and do not directly affect B cell function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe two main calcineurin inhibitors are cyclosporine, which binds to cyclophilin, and tacrolimus, which binds to FK-binding protein. Both ultimately prevent T cell activation and proliferation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Calcineurin inhibitors prevent T cell activation by blocking the calcineurin-mediated dephosphorylation of nuclear factor of activated T cells.","The two main calcineurin inhibitors are cyclosporine and tacrolimus, which are used to prevent organ transplant rejection.","Calcineurin inhibitors work by binding to immunophilins, forming complexes that inhibit calcineurin phosphatase activity."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62895"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17060"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62895","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62895"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T21:20:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T21:22:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9750"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77388"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"